{"title_page": "Peter Capaldi", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Peter Capaldi\n| image        = Peter Capaldi by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption      = Capaldi at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name   = Peter Dougan Capaldi\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1958|04|14}}\n| birth_place  = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| alma_mater   = [[Glasgow School of Art]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actor|director|writer|singer}}\n| years_active = 1982\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Elaine Collins|1991}}\n| children     = 1\n| relatives    = [[Lewis Capaldi]] <small>(second cousin once removed)</small>\n| signature    = Actor Peter Capaldi's signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Peter Dougan Capaldi''' (born 14 April 1958) is a Scottish actor, writer, director, and singer. He portrayed the [[Twelfth Doctor|twelfth incarnation]] of [[The Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor]] in ''[[Doctor Who]]'' (2013\u20132017) and [[Malcolm Tucker]] in ''[[The Thick of It]]'', for which he has received four [[British Academy Television Award]] nominations, winning [[British Academy Television Award for Best Male Comedy Performance|Best Male Comedy Performance]] in 2010. When he reprised the role of Tucker in the feature film ''[[In the Loop]]'', Capaldi was honoured with several film critic award nominations for Best Supporting Actor.\n\nAs a director, Capaldi won the [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film]] and the [[BAFTA Award for Best Short Film]] for his short film ''[[Franz Kafka's It's a Wonderful Life]]''. He went on to write and direct the drama film ''[[Strictly Sinatra]]'' and directed two series of the sitcom ''[[Getting On (UK TV series)|Getting On]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nCapaldi was born in [[Glasgow]], Scotland, to Nancy (''n\u00e9e'' Soutar) and Gerald John Capaldi.{{cn|date=November 2019}} His paternal grandfather was Italian while the rest of his ancestry is Scottish and Irish.<ref name=\"herald.scotland\">{{cite news|last=Dalgarno|first=Paul|title=Thick & Spin|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/thick-spin-1.836809|accessdate=5 June 2010|website=[[Herald Scotland]]|date=5 April 2008}}</ref> His parents ran an ice cream business in the [[Springburn]] district, where they were neighbours and acquaintances of the family of [[Armando Iannucci]], creator of ''The Thick of It'', although the two men did not know each other as children.<ref name=\"indy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/armando-iannucci-how-i-conquered-america-7869871.html|title=Armando Iannucci: 'How I conquered America'|last=Gilbert|first=Gerard|date=23 June 2012|website=[[independent.co.uk]]|accessdate=18 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/peter-capaldi-people-ask-me-to-tell-them-to--off-2264021.html|title=Peter Capaldi: 'People ask me to tell them to #@*! off'|website=The Independent|date=9 April 2011}}</ref> He was educated at St Teresa's Primary School in [[Possilpark]],<ref name=\"gazeteer\">{{cite web|title=Famous People Search \u2013 Peter Capaldi|url=http://www.scottish-places.info/people/famousfirst1752.html |website=[[Gazetteer for Scotland]]|accessdate=5 June 2010}}</ref> St Matthew's Primary School in [[Bishopbriggs]],<ref name=\"gazeteer\" /> and [[St Ninian's High School, Kirkintilloch]],<ref>{{cite web | title=St Ninian's High School \u2013 Famous Ex Pupils | url=http://www.st-ninians.e-dunbarton.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?section=Famous+Ex+Pupils&sid=133 | accessdate=14 September 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712140345/http://www.st-ninians.e-dunbarton.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?section=Famous+Ex+Pupils&sid=133# | archive-date=12 July 2015 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> before attending the [[Glasgow School of Art]].\n\nCapaldi displayed an early talent for performance by putting on a [[puppet]] show in primary school. While at high school, he was a member of the Antonine Players, who performed at the Fort Theatre in Bishopbriggs. As an art student, he was the lead singer and guitarist in a [[punk rock]] band called ''The Dreamboys'', whose drummer was future comedian [[Craig Ferguson]].<ref>{{cite news | title=No more Mr Nice Guy| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/aug/31/broadcasting.arts | accessdate=26 September 2009 |website=The Guardian | location=London | first=Stuart | last=Jeffries | date=31 August 2006}}</ref><ref>Ferguson, Craig: ''American on Purpose''. Harper Collins, 2009.</ref> The pair also performed a cabaret act together as ''Bing & Dean Hitler''<ref>{{cite web |title=Music List: Bing Hitler |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1986-05-02/15/ |website=The List |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=2 May 1986}}</ref> and wrote an alternative [[pantomime]] of Sleeping Beauty.<ref>{{cite web |title=Winter for Hitler |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1986-10-03/5/ |website=The List |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=3 October 1986}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Panto Time Again! |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1986-11-28/20/ |website=The List |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=28 November 1986}}</ref> Capaldi went on to perform musical comedy cabaret in the guises of \"bank clerk about town\" ''Gavin Meekie''<ref>{{cite web |title=MayFest: Day by Day Diary |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1987-05-01/12/ |website=The List |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=1 May 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Theatre List: Peter Capaldi |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1987-05-15/32/ |website=The List |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=15 May 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Andrew |title=5 Past 11 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DA41AAAAIBAJ&sjid=o6ULAAAAIBAJ&pg=2550%2C3393126 |website=Google News Archive |publisher=Glasgow Herald |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=18 January 1988}}</ref> and as one half of husband-and-wife TV evangelists ''Tom & Sammy Jo''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Theatre List: The Tom and Sammy Jo Show |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1988-04-15/27/ |website=The List |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=15 April 1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Billen |first1=Nigel |title=MayFest Reviews: The Tom and Sammy Jo Show |url=https://archive.list.co.uk/the-list/1988-05-13/15/ |website=The List |accessdate=4 July 2019 |date=13 May 1988}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nCapaldi has appeared in over 40 films and television shows since his appearance as Danny Oldsen in ''[[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]]'' (1983). He played Beatles member [[George Harrison]] in ''[[John and Yoko: A Love Story]]'' (1985), had roles in ''[[The Lair of the White Worm (film)|The Lair of the White Worm]]'' (1988) and ''[[Dangerous Liaisons]]'' (1988), and was featured as Ozzy in a 1985 episode of ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]''. He voiced Chief Petty Officer Grieves in the [[BBC Radio]] [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] comedy ''[[Our Brave Boys]]''. Capaldi's first starring role on television was as Luke Wakefield, a strange man who imagines he has witnessed a crime, in the [[BBC]] drama series ''Mr Wakefield's Crusade''. He played fictional ''[[Songs of Praise]]'' producer Tristan Campbell in two episodes of the sitcom ''[[The Vicar of Dibley]]'', and a [[transgender woman]] in [[ITV Studios|ITV]]'s ''[[Prime Suspect]]''. In [[Neil Gaiman]]'s gothic fantasy ''[[Neverwhere]]'', he portrayed the [[angel]] Islington.\n\nCapaldi is also an [[audiobook]] narrator, and his many titles include several of the works of [[Iain Banks]]. He starred as Rory in the 1996 television version of Banks's ''[[The Crow Road (TV series)|The Crow Road]]''.\n\n[[File:Peter Capaldi 2009 (cropped).jpg|upright|thumbnail|left|Peter Capaldi in 2009]]\n\nIn the 1999 [[Channel 4]] series ''Psychos'', he played a mathematician with [[bipolar disorder]].<ref name=\"psychos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/psychos/4od|title=Psychos at Channel 4|website=channel4.com}}</ref> Capaldi made an appearance as a [[university professor]] in the sitcom ''[[Peep Show (TV series)|Peep Show]]'', and played a [[prime suspect]] in the 2007 series of ''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]''. In 2007, Capaldi appeared as Mark Jenkins ([[Sid Jenkins|Sid]]'s dad) in the [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] teen comedy drama series ''[[Skins (UK TV series)|Skins]]''. He returned for a second series in 2008 although he died in the third episode. He appeared in the ''[[Midsomer Murders]]'' episode \"Death in Chorus\" and ITV1's ''[[Fallen Angel (UK TV series)|Fallen Angel]]''. He also appeared in the 2007 British comedy film ''[[Magicians (2007 film)|Magicians]]''.\n\nHe appeared as [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] in the Channel 4 series ''[[The Devil's Whore]]'', aired in 2008. Capaldi provided his voice for the [[animated film]] ''Haunted Hogmanay'' in 2006. He played Balthazar, one of the [[Biblical Magi]], in the 2010 BBC adaptation of ''[[The Nativity]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/04_april/30/nativity.shtml |title=Press Office \u2013 Stars align for Tony Jordan's Nativity on BBC One this Christmas |website=BBC |date= |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, he began playing Professor Marcus in ''[[The Ladykillers]]'' at the [[Liverpool Playhouse]], then transferred to the [[Gielgud Theatre]] in London. The original run closed at the Gielgud on 14 April 2012. He appeared in ''[[The Field of Blood (TV series)|The Field of Blood]]'' as Dr Pete, for which he received a [[BAFTA Scotland]] nomination in the TV actor/actress category; he was beaten by his co-star [[Jayd Johnson]]. He had a small role as a [[therapist]] in ''[[Big Fat Gypsy Gangster]]'', written by and starring his ''Getting On'' co-star [[Ricky Grover]]. In 2012, Capaldi played Randall Brown, the new Head of News, on the [[BBC2]] drama ''[[The Hour (2011 TV series)|The Hour]]''. He appeared as a [[World Health Organization|WHO]] doctor in ''[[World War Z (film)|World War Z]]'' (2013),<ref>{{cite web|author=Flicks and the City |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yeio4XGMobs |title=Peter Capaldi Interview \u2013 W.H.O. Doctor in World War Z & Maleficent |website=YouTube |date=10 December 2012 |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> and had a role in ''[[Maleficent (film)|Maleficent]]'' (2014), but his part in the latter film was cut during post-production.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bibbiani|first=William|title=Maleficent: Director Robert Stromberg on True Love and Reshoots|url=http://www.craveonline.com/film/interviews/695289-maleficent-director-robert-stromberg-on-true-love-and-reshoots|website=CraveOnline|accessdate=5 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe starred in ''Inside the Mind of Leonardo'', a documentary about [[Leonardo da Vinci]]. In 2013 he portrayed [[Alan Rusbridger]], the editor of [[The Guardian]] in ''[[The Fifth Estate (film)|The Fifth Estate]]''. In 2014 he starred in a new adaptation of ''[[The Three Musketeers]]'' as [[Cardinal Richelieu]] on [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Jordan Howell Follow @jordanhowell |url=http://www.imediamonkey.com/2013/02/26/peter-capaldi-luke-pasqualino-for-bbc-ones-the-musketeers/ |title=Peter Capaldi, Luke Pasqualino for BBC One's 'The Musketeers' &#124; News, UK TV &#124; imediamonkey\u00ae |website=Imediamonkey.com |accessdate=17 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607002908/http://www.imediamonkey.com/2013/02/26/peter-capaldi-luke-pasqualino-for-bbc-ones-the-musketeers/ |archivedate=7 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHe appeared as [[Paddington Bear]]'s neighbour Mr Curry in the family comedy film ''[[Paddington (film)|Paddington]]'' and its sequel ''[[Paddington 2]]''. In 2018, he voiced [[Rabbit (Winnie-the-Pooh)|Rabbit]] in the Disney film ''[[Christopher Robin (film)|Christopher Robin]]''.\n\n===Malcolm Tucker===\nPrior to taking over the lead role in ''[[Doctor Who]]'', Capaldi was best known for playing [[spin doctor]] [[Malcolm Tucker]] in the Armando Iannucci-written BBC sitcom ''[[The Thick of It]]'', which he played from 2005 to 2012. Tucker is said to be largely, if loosely, based upon [[Tony Blair]]'s right-hand man [[Alastair Campbell]], although Capaldi has said that he based his performance more on Hollywood power players, such as the often abrasive [[Harvey Weinstein]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Wardrop |first=Murray |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/9049658/Peter-Capaldi-Thick-Of-It-spin-doctor-Malcolm-Tucker-was-not-based-on-Alastair-Campbell.html |title=Peter Capaldi: 'Thick Of It spin doctor Malcolm Tucker was not based on Alastair Campbell' |website=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> A film spin-off from ''The Thick of It'' called ''[[In the Loop]]'' (in which Capaldi returned to the role of Tucker), was released in 2009.\n\nThe role of Tucker won Capaldi several awards. In 2006, 2008 and 2010 he was nominated for the [[BAFTA]] and RTS Best Comedy Actor Awards. He won the [[British Academy Television Awards 2010|2010 BAFTA Television Award]] for Male [[British Academy Television Award for Best Comedy Performance|Performance in a Comedy Role]].<ref name=\"bafta.2010.win\">{{cite web|title=Television Awards Winners in 2010 |url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/television/television-awards-nominations-in-2010,1095,BA.html |website=[[BAFTA]] |accessdate=6 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530211603/http://www.bafta.org/awards/television/television-awards-nominations-in-2010,1095,BA.html |archivedate=30 May 2010 }}</ref> He also won the 2010 and 2012 British Comedy Award for Best TV Comedy Actor.<ref>[http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a299572/in-full-british-comedy-awards-winners.html British Comedy Awards Winners] DigitalSpy 22 January 2011</ref> He received another BAFTA Award nomination in 2013.\n\n===''Doctor Who''===\n[[File:Peter Capaldi June 2014.jpg|right|thumb|Capaldi filming for ''[[Doctor Who (series 8)|Doctor Who]]'' in [[Cardiff]] in June 2014]]\nCapaldi was cast in 2013 as [[Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor]] in the BBC science-fiction series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. His casting was announced on 4 August 2013 in a special BBC programme hosted by [[Zo\u00eb Ball]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-23570354 |title=Doctor Who: Peter Capaldi revealed as 12th Doctor|website=[[BBC News]]|date=4 August 2013|accessdate=10 November 2014|publisher=BBC|archivedate=27 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427073433/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-23570354}}</ref> Capaldi first appeared as the Doctor in a cameo in the 50th anniversary special, \"[[The Day of the Doctor]]\", before appearing in the 2013 Christmas special, \"[[The Time of the Doctor]]\". A lifelong fan of the series, Capaldi had previously played Lobus Caecilius in the 2008 episode \"[[The Fires of Pompeii]]\" with the [[Tenth Doctor]] and his companion [[Donna Noble]], as well as playing civil servant [[John Frobisher]] in the 2009 spin-off ''[[Torchwood: Children of Earth]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Doctor Who sets the controls for Rome, AD 79|website=[[What's on TV]]|date=25 September 2007|url=http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/doctor-who/news/doctor-who-sets-the-controls-for-rome-ad-79|accessdate=10 November 2014|archivedate=10 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110190412/http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/doctor-who/news/doctor-who-sets-the-controls-for-rome-ad-79}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=BBC|website=[[BBC|BBC Press Office]]|title= Filming under way for new series of Torchwood|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/08_august/26/torchwood.shtml|date= 26 August 2008|accessdate= 10 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112194227/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/08_august/26/torchwood.shtml|archivedate=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nBefore taking the role, Capaldi stated that he had to seriously consider the increased level of visibility that would come with the part.<ref>{{cite news|title=Doctor Who: Peter Capaldi promises 'no flirting' with sidekick in new series|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/27/peter-capaldi-doctor-who-no-flirting-sidekick-coleman-new-series|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=27 July 2014|accessdate=10 November 2014|archivedate=28 August 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140828193914/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jul/27/peter-capaldi-doctor-who-no-flirting-sidekick-coleman-new-series}}</ref> He revealed in an interview with ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' that he had been invited to audition for the role of the [[Eighth Doctor]] in 1995 prior to the production of [[Doctor Who (film)|the 1996 TV film]], stating: \"I didn't go. I loved the show so much, and I didn't think I would get it, and I didn't want to just be part of a big [[Culling|cull]] of actors.\"<ref>{{cite news|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1 August 2014|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20741515_20839792_2,00.html|accessdate=10 November 2014|title=Once Upon a Time Lord|first=Clark|last=Collis|archivedate=10 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110192116/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20741515_20839792_2,00.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Capaldi voiced the Doctor on the [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]] website's game ''The Doctor and the Dalek'' and in 2015 voiced him in ''[[Lego Dimensions]]''. In 2016, Capaldi reprised his role as the [[Twelfth Doctor]] in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' spin-off programme ''[[Class (2016 TV series)|Class]]'', written by young-adult author [[Patrick Ness]].\n\nOn 30 January 2017, in an interview on BBC Radio 2, Capaldi confirmed that the tenth series would be his last.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-30/peter-capaldi-confirms-hes-leaving-doctor-who-at-the-end-of-series-10 |title=Peter Capaldi confirms he's leaving Doctor Who at the end of series 10 |website=[[Radio Times]] |first=Sarah |last=Doran |date=30 January 2017 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref> His final episode was the 2017 Christmas special, \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\".\n\n===Director, presenter and writer===\nIn 1992, Capaldi wrote and starred in the road movie ''[[Soft Top, Hard Shoulder]]'', which won the audience award at the [[London Film Festival]]. In 1995, he won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] for [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Best Live Action Short Film]] for his film ''[[Franz Kafka's It's a Wonderful Life]]'', which was tied with fellow nominee ''[[Trevor (film)|Trevor]]'', leading to both films being announced as joint winners, and won [[BAFTA Award for Best Short Film]] a year before that. He also wrote and directed ''[[Strictly Sinatra]]'' in 2001, and in 2009 he wrote and presented ''A Portrait of Scotland'', a documentary detailing 500 years' history of Scottish portrait painting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article6824979.ece|title=A Portrait of Scotland; Land Girls; Blue Murder|last=Billen|first=Andrew|date=8 September 2009 |website=The Times|accessdate=20 September 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nCapaldi directed several episodes of the 2009 [[BBC Four]] sitcom ''[[Getting On (UK TV series)|Getting On]]''.\n\nIn 2012, Capaldi wrote (with [[Tony Roche (writer)|Tony Roche]]), directed and performed in ''The Cricklewood Greats'', an affectionate spoof documentary about a fictitious film studio, which tracks real developments and trends throughout the history of British cinema, including silent movies, [[Hammer Film Productions|horror]] and [[Carry On (franchise)|bawdy comedy]], and a disastrous [[Terry Gilliam]] epic (Gilliam appears as himself).\n<!--\nIn 2013, Capaldi wrote and directed ''Born to be King''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/975790/Born-to-Be-King/ |title=Born to Be King (2014) \u2013 Overview |publisher=TCM.com |date= |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/mcgregor-and-hudson-topline-capaldi-hollywood-comedy-born-to-be-king |title=McGregor and Hudson Topline Capaldi Backstage Comedy 'Born To Be King' &#124; Thompson on Hollywood |website=Blogs.indiewire.com |date= |accessdate=27 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518135406/http://blogs.indiewire.com:80/thompsononhollywood/mcgregor-and-hudson-topline-capaldi-hollywood-comedy-born-to-be-king|archive-date=18 May 2016}}</ref> -->\n\n==Personal life==\nCapaldi married Elaine Collins in [[Strathblane Country House|Strathblane]] near his home city of Glasgow in 1991. Collins is an actress and writer; they met in 1983 in a touring production for the Paines Plough Theatre Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/peter-capaldi--wife-been-2129796#lAqpAIMWXoQwV1Ly.97|title=Doctor Who star Peter Capaldi : My wife has been the foundation for my career|last=McLean|first=Marc|website=dailyrecord|access-date=18 March 2016}}</ref> They live in [[Muswell Hill]] with their daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/peter-capaldi-interview-sexism-in-the-tv-industry-is-ridiculous-a3107436.html|title=Peter Capaldi interview: 'Sexism in the TV industry is ridiculous'|last=Thomas-Corr|first=Johanna|date=5 November 2015|website=[[Evening Standard]]|accessdate=5 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2016, Capaldi, with [[Cate Blanchett]], [[Chiwetel Ejiofor]], [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Douglas Booth]], [[Neil Gaiman]], [[Keira Knightley]], [[Juliet Stevenson]], [[Kit Harington]] and [[Stanley Tucci]], featured in a video from the [[United Nations System|United Nations']] refugee agency [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|UNHCR]] to help raise awareness about the global refugee crisis. ''\"What They Took With Them\"'' has the actors reading a poem, written by Jenifer Toksvig and inspired by primary accounts of refugees, and is part of UNHCR's #WithRefugees campaign, of which also includes a petition to governments to expand asylum to provide further shelter, integrating job opportunities, and education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refugeeday/stories/|title=2016 Stories \u2013 #WithRefugees|language=en-US|access-date=14 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refugeeday/what-they-took-with-them/|title=What They Took With Them \u2013 #WithRefugees|date=7 September 2016|language=en-US|access-date=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nCapaldi's second cousin once removed is singer-songwriter [[Lewis Capaldi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/music/music-news/rising-scottish-star-lewis-capaldi-12079123|title=Rising Scottish star Lewis Capaldi meets long-lost relative at London gig as Doctor Who appears|website=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref> The two worked together in the video for ''[[Someone You Loved]]''.\n\nCapaldi is a patron of [[Worldwide Cancer Research]], and the Scottish children's charity, the [[Aberlour Child Care Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aberlour.org.uk |title=Scotland's Children's Charity. Aberlour supports children, young people and families throughout Scotland |website=Aberlour |date= |accessdate=26 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1982 || ''Living Apart Together'' || Joe ||\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[Local Hero (film)|Local Hero]]'' || Danny Oldsen ||\n|-\n| 1984 || ''Bless My Soul'' || ||\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[Turtle Diary]]'' || Assistant keeper ||\n|-\n| 1987 || ''The Love Child'' || Dillon Flynn ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1988|| ''[[The Lair of the White Worm (film)|The Lair of the White Wo