{"title_page": "Rinat Yisrael", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n<!-- [[File:Rinat_Israel.JPG|thumb|right|''Siddur Rinat Yisrael'']] -->\n[[File:Amram Aburbeh Rinat Israel siddur Ha'Sfaradim ve'Edot HaMizrach.jpg||thumb|right|Title page of ''Nusach HaSfaradim and Edot HaMizrach''.]]\n[[File:IDF_soldier_put_on_tefillin.jpg||thumb|right|Israeli Soldier praying from a ''Siddur Rinat Yisrael''.]]\n'''Rinat Yisrael''' is a family of [[siddur]]im (prayer books), popular within the [[Religious Zionist]]  communities in [[Israel]]; and used by some (and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] in the [[Jewish diaspora|Diaspora]].\nThey are available in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] only. \nThe siddur was first published in 1970 by the [[Moreshet Publishing Company]], and edited by Dr. [[:he:\u05e9\u05dc\u05de\u05d4_\u05d8\u05dc |Shlomo Tal]]. \n\nPublished in connection with the [[Israeli Ministry of Education]], the siddur aims to allow youngsters and students to become familiar and comfortable with the siddur and [[Jewish services|prayer service]]. To further this goal, Rinat Yisrael uses a large [[typeface]], a modern, easy to read [[font]] ([[:he:\u05e4\u05e8\u05e0\u05e7-\u05e8\u05d9\u05d4\u05dc|Frank-R\u00fchl]]) and uses special symbols to denote which syllable a word is accented on. \n\nAlso included are references to verses quoted from the [[Tanakh]], and translations of difficult words, including passages in [[Aramaic]], into [[modern Hebrew]]. Additionally, most passages are printed in the same size type, in order not to lend the impression that some prayers are more important than others (see similar re the [[Birnbaum siddur]]).\n\nNew prayers recognizing the rebirth of the State of [[Israel]] have been added, including a [[Prayer for the Welfare of the State of Israel]], a Prayer for the Soldiers of The [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]], and a service for [[Israel Independence Day]].\n\nRinat Yisrael has been published in three different versions, or ''[[Nusach|Nuschaot]]'': [[Nusach Ashkenaz|Ashkenaz]] (published in both Israel and Diaspora versions), [[Nusach Sefard|Sefard]], and [[Sephardic]] / [[Edot HaMizrach]]. Rabbi [[Amram Aburbeh]] edited the latter.  The siddurim are published in various sizes.\n\nAlong with the siddur, other publications in the Rinat Yisrael series include [[machzor]]im for [[Rosh Hashanah]], [[Yom Kippur]], [[Sukkot]], [[Pesach]], and [[Shavuot]]; a [[haggadah]]; a book of [[selichot]], and a book of ''[[kinnot]]'' for [[Tisha B'av]]. These are all produced in different versions, as the prayer book above.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Koren Siddur]]\n\n[[Category:Siddur versions]]\n[[Category:Religious_Zionism]]\n[[Category:1970 non-fiction books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n<!-- [[File:Rinat_Israel.JPG|thumb|right|''Siddur Rinat Yisrael'']] -->\n[[File:Amram Aburbeh Rinat Israel siddur Ha'Sfaradim ve'Edot HaMizrach.jpg||thumb|right|Title page of ''Nusach HaSfaradim and Edot HaMizrach''.]]\n[[File:IDF_soldier_put_on_tefillin.jpg||thumb|right|Israeli Soldier praying from a ''Siddur Rinat Yisrael''.]]\n'''Rinat Yisrael''' is a family of [[siddur]]im (prayer books), popular within the [[Religious Zionist]] (and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]]) communities in [[Israel]], and used by some in the [[Jewish diaspora|Diaspora]]; They are available in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] only. \nThe siddur was first published in 1970 by the [[Moreshet Publishing Company]], and edited by Dr. [[:he:\u05e9\u05dc\u05de\u05d4_\u05d8\u05dc |Shlomo Tal]]. \n\nPublished in connection with the [[Israeli Ministry of Education]], the siddur aims to allow youngsters and students to become familiar and comfortable with the siddur and [[Jewish services|prayer service]]. To further this goal, Rinat Yisrael uses a large [[typeface]], a modern, easy to read [[font]] ([[:he:\u05e4\u05e8\u05e0\u05e7-\u05e8\u05d9\u05d4\u05dc|Frank-R\u00fchl]]) and uses special symbols to denote which syllable a word is accented on. Also included are references to verses quoted from the [[Tanakh]], and translations of difficult words, including passages in [[Aramaic]], into [[modern Hebrew]]. Additionally, most passages are printed in the same size type, in order not to lend the impression that some prayers are more important than others (see similar re the [[Birnbaum siddur]]).\n\nNew prayers recognizing the rebirth of the State of [[Israel]] have been added, including a [[Prayer for the Welfare of the State of Israel]], a Prayer for the Soldiers of The [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]], and a service for [[Israel Independence Day]].\n\nRinat Yisrael has been published in three different versions, or ''[[Nusach|Nuschaot]]'': [[Nusach Ashkenaz|Ashkenaz]] (published in both Israel and Diaspora versions), [[Nusach Sefard|Sefard]], and [[Sephardic]] / [[Edot HaMizrach]]. Rabbi [[Amram Aburbeh]] edited the latter.  The siddurim are published in various sizes.\n\nAlong with the siddur, other publications in the Rinat Yisrael series include [[machzor]]im for [[Rosh Hashanah]], [[Yom Kippur]], [[Sukkot]], [[Pesach]], and [[Shavuot]]; a [[haggadah]]; a book of [[selichot]], and a book of ''[[kinnot]]'' for [[Tisha B'av]]. These are all produced in different versions, as the prayer book above.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Koren Siddur]]\n\n[[Category:Siddur versions]]\n[[Category:Religious_Zionism]]\n[[Category:1970 non-fiction books]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rinat_Yisrael"}
{"title_page": "Lucas Prado", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = yellow\n| name             = Lucas Prado\n| image            = Lucas Prado - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| image_size       = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels. !-->\n| caption          = Prado at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]].\n| birth_name       = \n| full_name        = \n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = Brazilian\n| residence        = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1985|5|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Mato Grosso]], Brazil\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| height           = <!-- {{convert| |cm|ftin}} (2012) !-->\n| weight           = <!-- {{convert| |kg|lb}} (2012) !-->\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} !-->\n| country          = Brazil\n| sport            = Athletics\n| event            = \n| collegeteam      = \n| club             = \n| team             = \n| turnedpro        = \n| coach            = \n| retired          = \n| coaching         = \n| worlds           = \n| regionals        = \n| nationals        = \n| olympics         = \n| paralympics      = \n| highestranking   = \n| pb               = \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[para athletics]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{BRA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Paralympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres T11|100 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 200 metres T11|200 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Athletics at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 400 metres T11|400 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metres T11|100 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 400 metres T11|400 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]] | [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100 m T11]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Parapan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2015 Parapan American Games|2015 Toronto]] | [[Athletics at the 2015 Parapan American Games \u2013 Men's 100 metres T11|100 m T11]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Lucas Prado''' (born May 27, 1985 in [[Mato Grosso]]) is a visually impaired Brazilian athlete. He lost 90% of his vision in 2003 due to retinal detachment. He was introduced to track by friend and Paralympian [[Terezinha Guilhermina]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=681503 |title=Prado, Lucas |accessdate=18 October 2015 |work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001105136/http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=681503 |archive-date=1 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe won three gold medals in track for [[Brazil at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]], setting a world record,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-09/09/content_9887244.htm |title=Xinhua |access-date=2010-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106234538/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-09/09/content_9887244.htm |archive-date=2012-11-06 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.estadao.com.br/esportes/pequim2008/not_esp240908,0.shtm |title=Brazilian site (In Portuguese) |access-date=2010-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921232200/http://www.estadao.com.br/esportes/pequim2008/not_esp240908,0.shtm |archive-date=2012-09-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won two silver medals running 100m and 400m during the [[London 2012 Paralympic Games]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/19082588 |title=BBC Sport \u2013 Paralympic results |access-date=2018-02-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151024155058/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/19082588 |archive-date=2015-10-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=lucas-prado|old_id=681503}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prado, Lucas}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Mato Grosso]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-athletics-bio-stub}}\n{{Brazil-Paralympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor      = yellow\n| name             = Lucas Prado\n| image            = Lucas Prado - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| image_size       = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels. !-->\n| caption          = Lucas Prado at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]].\n| birth_name       = \n| full_name        = \n| nickname         = \n| nationality     