s-andersons-the-french-dispatch-casts-henry-winkler-and-hires-stunt-coordinator-dominique-fouassier/ |title=WES ANDERSON'S 'THE FRENCH DISPATCH' CASTS HENRY WINKLER AND HIRES STUNT COORDINATOR DOMINIQUE FOUASSIER |last=Tyler |first=Jacob |date=January 10, 2019 |website=thegww.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111234048/https://thegww.com/wes-andersons-the-french-dispatch-casts-henry-winkler-and-hires-stunt-coordinator-dominique-fouassier/ |archive-date=January 11, 2019 |access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> In February 2019, it was announced [[Wally Wolodarsky]], [[Fisher Stevens]], [[Griffin Dunne]], and [[Jason Schwartzman]] had joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bt6U4fWApNO/ |title=Boxes in the wardrobe department for Wes Anderson's \"The French Dispatch\" where the brilliant costumer Milena Canonero keeps the belongings of the characters. The only time I'll get top billing over Bill Murray so I'd better get a pic of it. |last=Dunne |first=Griffin |date=February 15, 2019 |website=[[Instagram.com]] |access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, [[Christoph Waltz]], [[Rupert Friend]], and [[Elisabeth Moss]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theplaylist.net/wes-anderson-christoph-waltz-french-dispatch-20190415/ |title=Wes Anderson Says Christoph Waltz Has Small Role In 'The French Dispatch' & Reveals More Details Including Possible Late-2019 Release |last=Barfield |first=Charles |date=April 15, 2019 |website=The Playlist |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415211508/https://theplaylist.net/wes-anderson-christoph-waltz-french-dispatch-20190415/ |archive-date=April 15, 2019 |access-date=April 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/elisabeth-moss-feminist-invisible-man-reboot-her-smell-1204707 |title=Elisabeth Moss on 'Her Smell' and a Feminist Take on 'The Invisible Man' |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425193735/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/elisabeth-moss-feminist-invisible-man-reboot-her-smell-1204707 |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Anderson, the film is set during the [[May 68]] riots in France. The trailer also describes the 1968 riots and that one of the 3 main storylines is completely based off of (or taken place during) the May 1968 French student riots and protests.\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began in November 2018, in the city of [[Angoul\u00eame]] (South-West France) and wrapped in March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.backstage.com/resources/detail/productionlisting/untitled-wes-anderson-project-86802/ |title=Untitled Wes Anderson Project |website=Backstage |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327090623/https://www.backstage.com/resources/detail/productionlisting/untitled-wes-anderson-project-86802/ |archive-date=March 27, 2019 |access-date=December 2, 2018}}</ref> Murray who has a small role in the film shot his scenes over the course of two days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theplaylist.net/wes-anderson-christoph-waltz-french-dispatch-20190415/|title=Wes Anderson Says Christoph Waltz Has Small Role In \u2018The French Dispatch\u2019 & Reveals More Details Including Possible Late-2019 Release|website=The Playlist|first=Charles|last=Barfield|date=April 15, 2019|accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe film's poster, drawn by Javi Aznarez, was revealed on February 11, 2020. The first trailer premiered the following day on February 12.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2020/film/news/the-french-dispatch-trailer-wes-anderson-1203500181/ | title = Wes Anderson\u2019s \u2018The French Dispatch\u2019 Debuts First Trailer | first=  Klaritza | last = Rico | date = February 12, 2020 | accessdate = February 12, 2020 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn September 2019, [[Searchlight Pictures]] acquired the worldwide rights to ''The French Dispatch''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/wes-anderson-french-dispatch-fox-searchlight-1202738541/ |title=Fox Searchlight Acquires World Rights To Wes Anderson's Upcoming Movie 'The French Dispatch' |last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |date=September 19, 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |url-status=live |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> It is scheduled to be released on July 24, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/wes-andersons-the-french-dispatch-gets-july-2020-release/|title=Wes Anderson\u2019s \u2018The French Dispatch\u2019 Gets July 2020 Release|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Brian|last=Welk|date=January 29, 2020|accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|tt8847712}}\n\n{{Wes Anderson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French Dispatch, The}}\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Wes Anderson]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in France]]\n[[Category:Fox Searchlight Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Babelsberg Studio films]]\n[[Category:Films partially in color]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_French_Dispatch"}
{"title_page": "Nouman Ali Khan", "text_new": "{{Undue weight|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nouman Ali Khan\n| image              = Nouman Ali Khan.jpg\n| caption            = Nouman Ali Khan in 2015\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Speaker\n| known_for          = Arabic and Quranic Studies\n| title              = Bayyinah Institute, founder\n| awards             = 500 Most Influential Muslim\n| website            = {{URL|www.bayyinah.com}}<br>{{URL|www.bayyinah.tv}}\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Nouman Ali Khan''' is a [[Pakistani-American]]<ref>Hussein Kesvani, ''Follow Me, Akhi: The Online World of British Muslims'', Oxford University Press, 2019, p. 17</ref> [[Da'i|Muslim speaker]] and Arabic instructor who founded the Bayyinah Institute for Arabic and Qur\u2019anic Studies after serving as an instructor of [[Arabic]] at [[Nassau Community College]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://theMuslim500.com/profile/khan-nouman-ali | title=The Muslim 500: Nouman Ali Khan | accessdate=2015-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/national-international/Imams-US-Mosques-Islam-224710772.html | title=Demand for U.S.-Born Imams Up in American Mosques | first=Gillian | last=Flaccus | date=2013-09-21 | accessdate=2015-06-17}}</ref> He has been named one of the 500 most influential Muslims in the world by the Royal Islamic Strategic Studies Centre of Jordan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themuslim500.com/profile/khan-nouman-ali | title=The Muslim 500: Nouman Ali Khan}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKhan was born in Germany to a Pakistani family and spent his preschool years in the former East Berlin.<ref>http://www.timeskuwait.com/Times_Nouman-Ali-Khan---The-Man--The-Mission-and-The-Media \"Nouman Ali Khan - The Man, The Mission and The Media\", ''The Times Kuwait'', 17 February 2015.</ref> His father then worked for the Pakistan Embassy in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, where Khan attended the Pakistan Embassy school from grades 2 to 8. His father moved the family to New York when Khan was in his teens.<ref>http://www.arabnews.com/news/445647 Sameen Tahir Khan, \"Nouman Khan: The one-man Qur\u2019an movement\", ''Arab News'', 22 March 2013.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\nPublications By Nouman Ali Khan\n!Title\n!Description\n!Date\n!Language\n|-\n|''Divine Speech: Exploring Quran As Literature''\n|Bayyinah Publishing in 2016\n|2016\n|English\n|-\n|''Revive Your Heart: Putting Life in Perspective''\n|Kube Publishing {{ISBN|978-0986275043}}\n|2017\n|English\n|-\n|''Bondhon''\n|Guardian Publication; 1st edition '''ASIN:''' B07KV37PVR\n|2010\n|Bangla\n|-\n|''Arabic With Husna''\n|Multiple Volumes {{ISBN|978-0986275043}}\n|\n|English\n|-\n|''Dirilt Kalbini''\n|Tima\u015f Yay\u0131nlar\u0131 (2017) {{ISBN|978-6050825992}}\n|\n|[[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n|-\n|''Revive Your Heart''\n|Guardian Publication\n|2019\n|[[Bangla language|Bangla]]\n|}\n''Divine Speech: Exploring Quran As Literature'', self-published by Bayyinah in 2016,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Divine Speech|last=Khan|first=Nouman Ali|last2=Randhawa|first2=Sharif|date=2016-01-01|publisher=Bayyinah Publications|isbn=9780986275050|edition=1st|language=English}}</ref> and ''Revive Your Heart: Putting Life in Perspective'', published by Kube Publishing in 2017.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Revive Your Heart: Putting Life in Perspective|last=Khan|first=Nouman Ali|date=2017-05-16|publisher=Kube Publishing Ltd|isbn=9781847741011|location=Place of publication not identified|language=English}}</ref> He has also co-authored and self-published two Arabic textbooks for Bayyinah courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=dp_byline_sr_book_1?ie=UTF8&text=Nouman+Ali+Khan&search-alias=books&field-author=Nouman+Ali+Khan&sort=relevancerank|title=Amazon.com: Nouman Ali Khan: Books|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2017-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==Accusations of harassment==\nIn September 2017, Khan was accused of inappropriate on-line interactions with numerous women, as reported in an article in ''[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]'' newspaper.<ref name=\"TheNational\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/muslim-western-communities-must-work-harder-to-protect-the-vulnerable-1.666533|title= Muslim western communities must work harder to protect the vulnerable|accessdate=14 January 2018|author=HA Hellyer|publisher = The National, 11 October 2017}}</ref> These accusations were repeated in international newspapers;<ref name = \"Dawn\">{{cite web|title=Nouman Ali Khan urges for 'theatre-free environment' to investigate allegations against him|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1359745|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=24 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sohail|first1=Rahima|title=Pakistani-American preacher alleged to have inappropriate relations with women|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1514111/famous-pakistani-american-preacher-alleged-inappropriate-relations-women/|website=[[The Express Tribune]]|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"DhakaTribune\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/around-the-web/2017/09/28/celebrity-american-muslim-preacher-nouman-ali-khan-accused-sexting/|title= The Perils of #MeToo as a Muslim\n|accessdate=24 December 2017 |newspaper = [[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=28 September 2017}}</ref> Khan responded that the leaked text conversations were \"between consenting adults\" and that the women were marriage prospects, noting that he had been divorced for two years.<ref name = \"Dawn\"/> In December 2017, ''[[BuzzFeed]] News'' published an article on what it called Khan's \"spiritual abuse\" activities, claiming that he unsuccessfully begged four fellow clerics to not release a joint statement referring to \"secret sham marriages\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Allam|first1=Hannah|title=Inside The 'Spiritual Abuse' Allegations Against A Celebrity Preacher|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/hannahallam/payoffs-threats-and-sham-marriages-women-say-a-celebrity|website=[[BuzzFeed News]]|accessdate= 20 December 2017|date=20 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=|first1=|title=Muslim-Americans Face Challenges When Confronting Leader's Misconduct|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/01/01/574933314/muslim-americans-face-challenges-when-confronting-leaders-misconduct|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|accessdate= 16 January 2018|date=1 January 2018}}</ref> An article in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' noted some backlash against women who had accused Khan of misconduct.<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/12/tariq-ramadan-metoo/548642/|title= The Perils of #MeToo as a Muslim|accessdate=14 January 2018|first=Jalal |last=Baig|newspaper=[[The Atlantic]] |type=opinion| date=21 December 2017 |quote=Though Khan has not been charged with a crime, the fallout polarized the Muslim community. In cyberspace specifically, there was a barrage of mudslinging against female critics to coerce them into silence. The women involved in the scandal, who claimed to be threatened with lawsuits if they spoke up, were also maligned.}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2017, a committee composed of various Islamic scholars and community leaders, including those who have held leadership positions in the Islamic Society of North America, counselors and mental health professionals, released a statement after conducting their own investigation into the matter. Among the panel were Aisha Al-Adawiya, Salma Abugideiri, Tamara Gray, Altaf Husain, Mohamed Magid and Ingrid Mattson. The committee stated, \"It is with heavy hearts that we confirm that Br. Nouman has committed significant violations of trust, spiritual abuse and unethical behavior.\" The committee recommended that Khan \u201cface the consequences of his actions, and ... take a break from public life in order to get counselling and engage in acts of expiation.\u201d<ref name=\"A Statement Regarding Br. Nouman Ali Khan\">{{cite web|url=https://muslimmatters.org/2017/10/03/a-statement-regarding-br-nouman-ali-khan|title= A Statement Regarding Br. Nouman Ali Khan|accessdate=2 September 2019|publisher = Muslim Matters, 3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|bayyinah.com}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Nouman Ali}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:American people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:People from Berlin]]\n[[Category:American religious writers]]\n[[Category:American Islamists]]\n[[Category:Islamic television preachers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Undue weight|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nouman Ali Khan\n| image              = Nouman Ali Khan.jpg\n| caption            = Nouman Ali Khan in 2015\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Speaker\n| known_for          = Arabic and Quranic Studies\n| title              = Bayyinah Institute, founder\n| awards             = 500 Most Influential Muslim\n| website            = {{URL|www.bayyinah.com}}<br>{{URL|www.bayyinah.tv}}\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Nouman Ali Khan''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Da'i|Muslim speaker]] and Arabic instructor who founded the Bayyinah Institute for Arabic and Qur\u2019anic Studies after serving as an instructor of [[Arabic]] at [[Nassau Community College]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://theMuslim500.com/profile/khan-nouman-ali | title=The Muslim 500: Nouman Ali Khan | accessdate=2015-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/national-international/Imams-US-Mosques-Islam-224710772.html | title=Demand for U.S.-Born Imams Up in American Mosques | first=Gillian | last=Flaccus | date=2013-09-21 | accessdate=2015-06-17}}</ref> He has been named one of the 500 most influential Muslims in the world by the Royal Islamic Strategic Studies Centre of Jordan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themuslim500.com/profile/khan-nouman-ali | title=The Muslim 500: Nouman Ali Khan}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKhan was born in Germany to a Pakistani family and spent his preschool years in the former East Berlin.<ref>http://www.timeskuwait.com/Times_Nouman-Ali-Khan---The-Man--The-Mission-and-The-Media \"Nouman Ali Khan - The Man, The Mission and The Media\", ''The Times Kuwait'', 17 February 2015.</ref> His father then worked for the Pakistan Embassy in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, where Khan attended the Pakistan Embassy school from grades 2 to 8. His father moved the family to New York when Khan was in his teens.<ref>http://www.arabnews.com/news/445647 Sameen Tahir Khan, \"Nouman Khan: The one-man Qur\u2019an movement\", ''Arab News'', 22 March 2013.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\nPublications By Nouman Ali Khan\n!Title\n!Description\n!Date\n!Language\n|-\n|''Divine Speech: Exploring Quran As Literature''\n|Bayyinah Publishing in 2016\n|2016\n|English\n|-\n|''Revive Your Heart: Putting Life in Perspective''\n|Kube Publishing {{ISBN|978-0986275043}}\n|2017\n|English\n|-\n|''Bondhon''\n|Guardian Publication; 1st edition '''ASIN:''' B07KV37PVR\n|2010\n|Bangla\n|-\n|''Arabic With Husna''\n|Multiple Volumes {{ISBN|978-0986275043}}\n|\n|English\n|-\n|''Dirilt Kalbini''\n|Tima\u015f Yay\u0131nlar\u0131 (2017) {{ISBN|978-6050825992}}\n|\n|[[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n|-\n|''Revive Your Heart''\n|Guardian Publication\n|2019\n|[[Bangla language|Bangla]]\n|}\n''Divine Speech: Exploring Quran As Literature'', self-published by Bayyinah in 2016,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Divine Speech|last=Khan|first=Nouman Ali|last2=Randhawa|first2=Sharif|date=2016-01-01|publisher=Bayyinah Publications|isbn=9780986275050|edition=1st|language=English}}</ref> and ''Revive Your Heart: Putting Life in Perspective'', published by Kube Publishing in 2017.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Revive Your Heart: Putting Life in Perspective|last=Khan|first=Nouman Ali|date=2017-05-16|publisher=Kube Publishing Ltd|isbn=9781847741011|location=Place of publication not identified|language=English}}</ref> He has also co-authored and self-published two Arabic textbooks for Bayyinah courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=dp_byline_sr_book_1?ie=UTF8&text=Nouman+Ali+Khan&search-alias=books&field-author=Nouman+Ali+Khan&sort=relevancerank|title=Amazon.com: Nouman Ali Khan: Books|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2017-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==Accusations of harassment==\nIn September 2017, Khan was accused of inappropriate on-line interactions with numerous women, as reported in an article in ''[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]'' newspaper.<ref name=\"TheNational\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/opinion/muslim-western-communities-must-work-harder-to-protect-the-vulnerable-1.666533|title= Muslim western communities must work harder to protect the vulnerable|accessdate=14 January 2018|author=HA Hellyer|publisher = The National, 11 October 2017}}</ref> These accusations were repeated in international newspapers;<ref name = \"Dawn\">{{cite web|title=Nouman Ali Khan urges for 'theatre-free environment' to investigate allegations against him|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1359745|website=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=24 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sohail|first1=Rahima|title=Pakistani-American preacher alleged to have inappropriate relations with women|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1514111/famous-pakistani-american-preacher-alleged-inappropriate-relations-women/|website=[[The Express Tribune]]|accessdate=28 September 2017|date=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"DhakaTribune\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/around-the-web/2017/09/28/celebrity-american-muslim-preacher-nouman-ali-khan-accused-sexting/|title= The Perils of #MeToo as a Muslim\n|accessdate=24 December 2017 |newspaper = [[Dhaka Tribune]] |date=28 September 2017}}</ref> Khan responded that the leaked text conversations were \"between consenting adults\" and that the women were marriage prospects, noting that he had been divorced for two years.<ref name = \"Dawn\"/> In December 2017, ''[[BuzzFeed]] News'' published an article on what it called Khan's \"spiritual abuse\" activities, claiming that he unsuccessfully begged four fellow clerics to not release a joint statement referring to \"secret sham marriages\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Allam|first1=Hannah|title=Inside The 'Spiritual Abuse' Allegations Against A Celebrity Preacher|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/hannahallam/payoffs-threats-and-sham-marriages-women-say-a-celebrity|website=[[BuzzFeed News]]|accessdate= 20 December 2017|date=20 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=|first1=|title=Muslim-Americans Face Challenges When Confronting Leader's Misconduct|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/01/01/574933314/muslim-americans-face-challenges-when-confronting-leaders-misconduct|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|accessdate= 16 January 2018|date=1 January 2018}}</ref> An article in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' noted some backlash against women who had accused Khan of misconduct.<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/12/tariq-ramadan-metoo/548642/|title= The Perils of #MeToo as a Muslim|accessdate=14 January 2018|first=Jalal |last=Baig|newspaper=[[The Atlantic]] |type=opinion| date=21 December 2017 |quote=Though Khan has not been charged with a crime, the fallout polarized the Muslim community. In cyberspace specifically, there was a barrage of mudslinging against female critics to coerce them into silence. The women involved in the scandal, who claimed to be threatened with lawsuits if they spoke up, were also maligned.}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2017, a committee composed of various Islamic scholars and community leaders, including those who have held leadership positions in the Islamic Society of North America, counselors and mental health professionals, released a statement after conducting their own investigation into the matter. Among the panel were Aisha Al-Adawiya, Salma Abugideiri, Tamara Gray, Altaf Husain, Mohamed Magid and Ingrid Mattson. The committee stated, \"It is with heavy hearts that we confirm that Br. Nouman has committed significant violations of trust, spiritual abuse and unethical behavior.\" The committee recommended that Khan \u201cface the consequences of his actions, and ... take a break from public life in order to get counselling and engage in acts of expiation.\u201d<ref name=\"A Statement Regarding Br. Nouman Ali Khan\">{{cite web|url=https://muslimmatters.org/2017/10/03/a-statement-regarding-br-nouman-ali-khan|title= A Statement Regarding Br. Nouman Ali Khan|accessdate=2 September 2019|publisher = Muslim Matters, 3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|bayyinah.com}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Nouman Ali}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Dallas]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:American people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:People from Berlin]]\n[[Category:American religious writers]]\n[[Category:American Islamists]]\n[[Category:Islamic television preachers]]\n", "name_user": "Arslan-San", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nouman_Ali_Khan"}
{"title_page": "Aesthetic medicine", "text_new": "'''Aesthetic medicine''' is an extensively broad term for specialties that focus on improving cosmetic appearance through the treatment of conditions including [[scar]]s, skin laxity, wrinkles, moles, [[liver spot]]s, excess fat, [[cellulite]], unwanted hair, skin discoloration, and [[telangiectasia|spider veins]].  Traditionally, aesthetic medicine includes [[dermatology]], [[oral and maxillofacial surgery]], [[reconstructive surgery]] and [[plastic surgery]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.a4m.com/fellowship-aesthetic-overview-what-is-aesthetic-medicine.html|title=What is Aesthetic Medicine?|website=[[American Academy of Anti-Aging Medicine]]}}</ref>  Aesthetic medicine includes both surgical procedures ([[liposuction]], [[Rhytidectomy|facelifts]], [[breast implant]]s, [[Radio frequency ablation]]) and non-surgical procedures ([[Radio Frequency skin tightening|radio frequency skin tightening]], [[non surgical liposuction]], [[chemical peel]], [[high-intensity focused electromagnetic field]], [[radio frequency fat removal]]), and practitioners may utilize a combination of both.<ref>[http://www.iapam.com/aboutiapam ''International Association for Physicians in Aesthetic Medicine'', IAPAM.]</ref>  Although aesthetic medicine procedures are typically elective, they can significantly improve quality of life, psychological wellbeing and social engagement.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| issn = 0032-1052\n| volume = 113\n| issue = 4\n| pages = 1229\u20131237\n| last = Honigman\n| first = Roberta J.\n| author2 = Katharine A. Phillips, David J. Castle\n| title = A review of psychosocial outcomes for patients seeking cosmetic surgery\n| journal = Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery\n| date = 2004-04-01\n| pmid = 15083026\n| pmc = 1762095\n| doi=10.1097/01.prs.0000110214.88868.ca}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\n*Worldwide, there were 20 million aesthetic procedures performed from 2014-2015.<ref>{{Cite report | publisher = International Society of Aesthetic Plastic Surgery | title = Statistics on Cosmetic Procedures Worldwide | url = http://www.isaps.org/Media/Default/Current%20News/ISAPS%202013%20Statistic%20Release%20FINAL%20(2).pdf | date = 2014 | access-date = 2015-01-14 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150131095818/http://www.isaps.org/media/default/current%20news/isaps%202013%20statistic%20release%20final%20(2).pdf | archivedate = 2015-01-31 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  Cosmetic surgery is a major driver of [[medical tourism]]. In February 2018 the president of the [[British Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons]] said operations were performed on people who were not appropriate for surgery, and that unscrupulous practitioners have endangered their health for profit and that the cost of rectification for more than 1000 patients a year fell on the British [[National Health Service]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Botched foreign cosmetic surgery leaves thousands of Brit health tourists scarred for life and NHS with \u00a330million bill|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/botched-foreign-cosmetic-surgery-leaves-12010331|accessdate=13 February 2018|publisher=Mirror|date=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n*Countries that performed the most aesthetic procedures in 2014 were<ref>{{Cite report |publisher = International Society of Aesthetic Plastic Surgery|title = Statistics on Cosmetic Procedures Worldwide|url = http://www.isaps.org/Media/Default/global-statistics/2015%20ISAPS%20Results.pdf|date = 2015}}</ref> {{ordered list | [[United States]] | [[Brazil]] | [[Japan]]| [[South Korea]]| [[Mexico]]}}\n*In the US, there were more than 11 million aesthetic procedures performed from 2012-2013, and 83.5% of the procedures were nonsurgical.<ref>{{Cite report | publisher = The American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery | title = Cosmetic Surgery National Data Bank Statistics | date = 2013\n}}</ref>\n*In the UK, there were 50,000 cosmetic surgery procedures performed in 2013-2014.<ref>{{Cite report | publisher = The British Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons | title = Britain sucks | location = London, UK | url = http://baaps.org.uk/about-us/press-releases/1833-britain-sucks | date = 2014 | access-date = 2015-01-14 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141227022559/http://baaps.org.uk/about-us/press-releases/1833-britain-sucks | archivedate = 2014-12-27 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n*Surgical aesthetic procedures account for 10% of the cosmetic procedures in the UK, and non surgical techniques constitute the remaining 90%.<ref>{{Cite report | publisher = UK Department of Health | title = Review of the Regulation of Cosmetic Interventions | url= https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/192028/Review_of_the_Regulation_of_Cosmetic_Interventions.pdf | date = 2013}}</ref>\n*In the US, the top 5 surgical aesthetic procedures were 1) [[Liposuction]] 2) [[Breast augmentation]] 3) [[Blepharoplasty]] 4) [[Abdominoplasty]] 5) [[Rhinoplasty]]<ref name=\"auto 1\">{{Cite report | publisher = The American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery | title = Cosmetic Surgery National Data Bank Statistics  | date = 2013}}</ref>\n*In the US, the top 5 nonsurgical aesthetic procedures were 1) [[Botulinum Toxin]] 2) [[Injectable filler#Material: Hyaluronic acid|Hyaluronic acid]] 3) [[Laser hair removal]] 4) [[Dermabrasion#Microdermabrasion|Microdermabrasion]] 5) [[Photorejuvenation]]<ref name=\"auto 1\" />\n*In South Korea, there were more than 980,000 aesthetic procedures performed from 2014-2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://bestkoreanplasticsurgery.com/korean-plastic-surgery/|title = Best Korean Plastic Surgery|date = December 27, 2015|accessdate = December 27, 2015|website = Best Korean Plastic Surgery - Guide to Information and Facts|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n*In South Korea, the top 5 surgical aesthetic procedures were 1) [[Blepharoplasty]] 2) [[Rhinoplasty]] 3) [[Liposuction|Fat Grafting]] 4) [[Rhytidectomy]] 5) [[Hair transplantation|Hair Transplantation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.isaps.org/Media/Default/global-statistics/2015%20ISAPS%20Results.pdf|title = ISAPS International Survey on Aesthetic/Cosmetic|date = July 8, 2015|accessdate = December 27, 2015|website = ISAPS|publisher = |last = ISAPS}}</ref>\n\n== Indications ==\n\nAesthetic medicine specializes in improving cosmetic appearance.  It has diverse applications for dermatological and surgical conditions.  It includes indications related to minimizing signs of aging such as skin laxity, wrinkles, and [[liver spot]]s.  Aesthetic medicine also plays a role in the treatment of excess fat, [[cellulite]] and obesity.  Laser based therapies can be indicated for the treatment of [[scar]]s, unwanted hair, skin discoloration, and [[telangiectasia|spider veins]].<ref>Medical Aesthetics Clinical Skin Protocols 2014</ref>\n\nIt is important that overall health is assessed by a physician to ensure that the symptom being treated (for example, weight gain and [[Hypertrichosis|excessive hair]]) is not a sign of an underlying medical condition (like hypothyroidism) that should be stabilized with medical therapies.\nIt is also very important for the medical aesthetician to be inclusive in providing a team approach for minimally invasive facial aesthetic procedures.\n\n== Techniques and procedures ==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Photorejuvenation]]\n* Injections of [[Botulinum toxin]] (Botox)\n* Injection of [[Injectable filler|dermal fillers]]\n* [[Cryolipolysis]]\n* [[Chemical peel|Chemical Peels]]\n* [[Mesotherapy]] injection\n* [[Cellulite]] treatment\n* [[Nutrition]]\n* [[Permanent makeup]]\n* [[Hair transplantation]]\n* [[Laser hair removal]]\n* [[Laser medicine|Laser Therapy]] for scars and stretch marks\n* [[Nd:YAG laser#Medicine|Nd:YAG laser]] for [[telangiectasia|spider veins]]\n* [[Contour threads]]\n* [[Non-surgical liposuction]]\n* [[Lipotomy]]\n* [[Carboxytherapy]]\n* [[Radio Frequency skin tightening]]\n* [[Tattoo removal|laser tattoo removal]]\n* [[Rhytidectomy|facelifts]]\n* [[Rhinoplasty]] \n* [[Abdominoplasty]]\n* [[Breast augmentation]] or [[Reduction mammoplasty|reduction]]\n* [[Brachioplasty]] \n* [[Liposuction]] \n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Careers in aesthetic medicine ==\n\nA career in aesthetic medicine can be approached from a number of professions.  A multidisciplinary or team based approach is often necessary to adequately address an aesthetic need.  To perform certain procedures, one must be a [[surgeon]], [[medical doctor]] (Dermatologist/plastic surgeon/ENT surgeon/Oculoplastic surgeon) or [[Cosmetic Dentist|maxillofacial surgeon /Cosmetic Dentist]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kaplan J., Volk A. S., Ashley J. R., Izaddoost S., Reece E., Winocour S. | year = 2019 | title = A Systematic Review of Resident Aesthetic Clinic Outcomes | url = | journal = Aesthetic surgery journal | volume =  39| issue = | pages =  NP387-NP395| doi = 10.1093/asj/sjz020 | pmid = 30715241 }}</ref>  However, many of the procedures are routinely performed by trained [[Medical Aestheticians]] or facial aesthetic nurse-aestheticians  [[Nursing|nurses]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Holmberg C., Carlstr\u00f6m E., Collier H. | year = 2019 | title = Registered nurses' perspectives on medically safe practices and sound ethical standards in aesthetic nursing: an interview study | url = | journal = Journal of Clinical Nursing | volume =  29| issue = | pages =  944\u2013954| doi = 10.1111/jocn.15158 | pmid = 31889344 }}</ref>  For example, [[Cosmetology|Medical Aesthetician]] can perform progressive chemical peels.  Medical Aesthetics requires specialized training and certification beyond a nurse license / aesthetic license. [[Mental health counselor|Counselors]], [[psychologist]]s or [[psychiatrist]]s can help people determine if their reasons for pursuing aesthetic procedures are healthy and help to identify psychiatric disorders such as [[Disordered eating|compulsive eating]], [[anorexia nervosa|anorexia]], and [[body dysmorphic disorder]]. [[Reconstructive surgery|Reconstructive surgeons]] can help correct appearance after accidents, burns, surgery for [[cancer]] (such as [[breast reconstruction]] after [[mastectomy]] for cancer), or for [[congenital deformities]] like correction of [[cleft lip]]. [[Orthodontists]] work to improve alignment of teeth, often partially for aesthetic reasons, and [[Oral and maxillofacial surgery|oral and maxillofacial surgeons]] can perform cosmetic facial surgery & correct deformities of the mouth and jaw.  Both orthodontists and maxillofacial surgeons can be assisted by [[dental technicians]]. [https://ameriaa.com/ American Aesthetic Association] (AAA)  providing all aesthetic diploma courses such as cosmetic gynecology, hair transplant, etc.  for physicians and surgeons to enhance their medical practice. Aesthetic Medicine is often a subset of other practices of medicine, for example a family physician who is board certified by the (AAFP) [[American Academy of Family Physicians]], may also offer aesthetic medicine treatments. Often physicians such as these will join multi-specialty associations, like the IAPAM ([[International Association for Physicians in Aesthetic Medicine]]) or ASLMS (American Society for Laser Medicine & Surgery) to further their education.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cosmetic surgery]]\n[[Category:Practice of medicine]]\n", "text_old": "'''Aesthetic medicine''' is an extensively broad term for specialties that focus on improving cosmetic appearance through the treatment of conditions including [[scar]]s, skin laxity, wrinkles, moles, [[liver spot]]s, excess fat, [[cellulite]], unwanted hair, skin discoloration, and [[telangiectasia|spider veins]].  Traditionally, aesthetic medicine includes [[dermatology]], [[oral and maxillofacial surgery]], [[reconstructive surgery]] and [[plastic surgery]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.a4m.com/fellowship-aesthetic-overview-what-is-aesthetic-medicine.html|title=What is Aesthetic Medicine?|website=[[American Academy of Anti-Aging Medicine]]}}</ref>  Aesthetic medicine includes both surgical procedures ([[liposuction]], [[Rhytidectomy|facelifts]], [[breast implant]]s, [[Radio frequency ablation]]) and non-surgical procedures ([[Radio Frequency skin tightening|radio frequency skin tightening]], [[non surgical liposuction]], [[chemical peel]], [[high-intensity focused electromagnetic field]], [[radio frequency fat removal]]), and practitioners may utilize a combination of both.<ref>[http://www.iapam.com/aboutiapam ''International Association for Physicians in Aesthetic Medicine'', IAPAM.]</ref>  Although aesthetic medicine procedures are typically elective, they can significantly improve quality of life, psychological wellbeing and social engagement.<ref>{{Cite journal\n| issn = 0032-1052\n| volume = 113\n| issue = 4\n| pages = 1229\u20131237\n| last = Honigman\n| first = Roberta J.\n| author2 = Katharine A. Phillips, David J. Castle\n| title = A review of psychosocial outcomes for patients seeking cosmetic surgery\n| journal = Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery\n| date = 2004-04-01\n| pmid = 15083026\n| pmc = 1762095\n| doi=10.1097/01.prs.0000110214.88868.ca}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\n*Worldwide, there were 20 million aesthetic procedures performed from 2014-2015.<ref>{{Cite report | publisher = International Society of Aesthetic Plastic Surgery | title = Statistics on Cosmetic Procedures Worldwide | url = http://www.isaps.org/Media/Default/Current%20News/ISAPS%202013%20Statistic%20Release%20FINAL%20(2).pdf | date = 2014 | access-date = 2015-01-14 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150131095818/http://www.isaps.org/media/default/current%20news/isaps%202013%20statistic%20release%20final%20(2).pdf | archivedate = 2015-01-31 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  Cosmetic surgery is a major driver of [[medical tourism]]. In February 2018 the president of the [[British Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons]] sai