le = Review of the Regulation of Cosmetic Interventions | url= https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/192028/Review_of_the_Regulation_of_Cosmetic_Interventions.pdf | date = 2013}}</ref>\n*In the US, the top 5 surgical aesthetic procedures were 1) [[Liposuction]] 2) [[Breast augmentation]] 3) [[Blepharoplasty]] 4) [[Abdominoplasty]] 5) [[Rhinoplasty]]<ref name=\"auto 1\">{{Cite report | publisher = The American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery | title = Cosmetic Surgery National Data Bank Statistics  | date = 2013}}</ref>\n*In the US, the top 5 nonsurgical aesthetic procedures were 1) [[Botulinum Toxin]] 2) [[Injectable filler#Material: Hyaluronic acid|Hyaluronic acid]] 3) [[Laser hair removal]] 4) [[Dermabrasion#Microdermabrasion|Microdermabrasion]] 5) [[Photorejuvenation]]<ref name=\"auto 1\" />\n*In South Korea, there were more than 980,000 aesthetic procedures performed from 2014-2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://bestkoreanplasticsurgery.com/korean-plastic-surgery/|title = Best Korean Plastic Surgery|date = December 27, 2015|accessdate = December 27, 2015|website = Best Korean Plastic Surgery - Guide to Information and Facts|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n*In South Korea, the top 5 surgical aesthetic procedures were 1) [[Blepharoplasty]] 2) [[Rhinoplasty]] 3) [[Liposuction|Fat Grafting]] 4) [[Rhytidectomy]] 5) [[Hair transplantation|Hair Transplantation]]<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.isaps.org/Media/Default/global-statistics/2015%20ISAPS%20Results.pdf|title = ISAPS International Survey on Aesthetic/Cosmetic|date = July 8, 2015|accessdate = December 27, 2015|website = ISAPS|publisher = |last = ISAPS}}</ref>\n\n== Indications ==\n\nAesthetic medicine specializes in improving cosmetic appearance.  It has diverse applications for dermatological and surgical conditions.  It includes indications related to minimizing signs of aging such as skin laxity, wrinkles, and [[liver spot]]s.  Aesthetic medicine also plays a role in the treatment of excess fat, [[cellulite]] and obesity.  Laser based therapies can be indicated for the treatment of [[scar]]s, unwanted hair, skin discoloration, and [[telangiectasia|spider veins]].<ref>Medical Aesthetics Clinical Skin Protocols 2014</ref>\n\nIt is important that overall health is assessed by a physician to ensure that the symptom being treated (for example, weight gain and [[Hypertrichosis|excessive hair]]) is not a sign of an underlying medical condition (like hypothyroidism) that should be stabilized with medical therapies.\nIt is also very important for the medical aesthetician to be inclusive in providing a team approach for minimally invasive facial aesthetic procedures.\n\n== Techniques and procedures ==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Photorejuvenation]]\n* Injections of [[Botulinum toxin]] (Botox)\n* Injection of [[Injectable filler|dermal fillers]]\n* [[Cryolipolysis]]\n* [[Chemical peel|Chemical Peels]]\n* [[Mesotherapy]] injection\n* [[Cellulite]] treatment\n* [[Nutrition]]\n* [[Permanent makeup]]\n* [[Hair transplantation]]\n* [[Laser hair removal]]\n* [[Laser medicine|Laser Therapy]] for scars and stretch marks\n* [[Nd:YAG laser#Medicine|Nd:YAG laser]] for [[telangiectasia|spider veins]]\n* [[Contour threads]]\n* [[Non-surgical liposuction]]\n* [[Lipotomy]]\n* [[Carboxytherapy]]\n* [[Radio Frequency skin tightening]]\n* [[Tattoo removal|laser tattoo removal]]\n* [[Rhytidectomy|facelifts]]\n* [[Rhinoplasty]] \n* [[Abdominoplasty]]\n* [[Breast augmentation]] or [[Reduction mammoplasty|reduction]]\n* [[Brachioplasty]] \n* [[Liposuction]] \n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Careers in aesthetic medicine ==\n\nA career in aesthetic medicine can be approached from a number of professions.  A multidisciplinary or team based approach is often necessary to adequately address an aesthetic need.  To perform certain procedures, one must be a [[surgeon]], [[medical doctor]] (Dermatologist/plastic surgeon/ENT surgeon/Oculoplastic surgeon) or [[Cosmetic Dentist|maxillofacial surgeon /Cosmetic Dentist]].<ref> Kaplan, J., Volk, A. S., Ashley, J. R., Izaddoost, S., Reece, E., & Winocour, S. (2019). A Systematic Review of Resident Aesthetic Clinic Outcomes. Aesthetic surgery journal. {{PMID|30715241}}. doi: 10.1093/asj/sjz020 </ref>  However, many of the procedures are routinely performed by trained [[Medical Aestheticians]] or facial aesthetic nurse-aestheticians  [[Nursing|nurses]]..<ref> Holmberg, C., Carlstr\u00f6m, E., & Collier, H. (2019). Registered nurses' perspectives on medically safe practices and sound ethical standards in aesthetic nursing: an interview study. Journal of Clinical Nursing. {{PMID|31889344}}. doi: https://doi.org/10.1111/jocn.15158. [Epub ahead of print] </ref>  For example, [[Cosmetology|Medical Aesthetician]] can perform progressive chemical peels.  Medical Aesthetics requires specialized training and certification beyond a nurse license / aesthetic license. [[Mental health counselor|Counselors]], [[psychologist]]s or [[psychiatrist]]s can help people determine if their reasons for pursuing aesthetic procedures are healthy and help to identify psychiatric disorders such as [[Disordered eating|compulsive eating]], [[anorexia nervosa|anorexia]], and [[body dysmorphic disorder]]. [[Reconstructive surgery|Reconstructive surgeons]] can help correct appearance after accidents, burns, surgery for [[cancer]] (such as [[breast reconstruction]] after [[mastectomy]] for cancer), or for [[congenital deformities]] like correction of [[cleft lip]]. [[Orthodontists]] work to improve alignment of teeth, often partially for aesthetic reasons, and [[Oral and maxillofacial surgery|oral and maxillofacial surgeons]] can perform cosmetic facial surgery & correct deformities of the mouth and jaw.  Both orthodontists and maxillofacial surgeons can be assisted by [[dental technicians]]. [https://ameriaa.com/ American Aesthetic Association] (AAA)  providing all aesthetic diploma courses such as cosmetic gynecology, hair transplant, etc.  for physicians and surgeons to enhance their medical practice. Aesthetic Medicine is often a subset of other practices of medicine, for example a family physician who is board certified by the (AAFP) [[American Academy of Family Physicians]], may also offer aesthetic medicine treatments. Often physicians such as these will join multi-specialty associations, like the IAPAM ([[International Association for Physicians in Aesthetic Medicine]]) or ASLMS (American Society for Laser Medicine & Surgery) to further their education.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cosmetic surgery]]\n[[Category:Practice of medicine]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aesthetic_medicine"}
